{"parentUuid":"f8a0ef32-ea23-45c3-983d-361ff199b7bb","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/robert/Code/mittwald-mcp/.worktrees/005-mcp-functional-test/tests/functional","sessionId":"a6859c6f-94af-4413-a237-8636fc18bf6e","version":"2.0.58","gitBranch":"feat/app-dependency-list","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01U9UCmqHe3fpZKV6jCTwYxv","type":"tool_result","content":"# Model Context Protocol (MCP) - Available Commands\n\nBased on the web page content, MCP itself is not a command-line tool with specific commands. Rather, it's **an open-source standard for connecting AI applications to external systems**.\n\n## What MCP Enables\n\nThe protocol allows AI applications to:\n\n- **Access data sources** (local files, databases)\n- **Utilize tools** (search engines, calculators)\n- **Execute workflows** (specialized prompts)\n\nThe page describes MCP as functioning \"like a USB-C port for AI applications,\" providing standardized connectivity.\n\n## Development Resources\n\nThe documentation outlines paths for developers:\n\n1. **Build MCP servers** - to expose data and tools\n2. **Build MCP clients** - applications that connect to MCP servers\n3. **Use SDKs** - official tools for implementation\n4. **MCP Inspector** - for testing and debugging servers\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nMCP is an **architectural standard and protocol**, not a command-line utility with discrete commands. Users interact with it through client applications (like Claude Desktop) that integrate with MCP servers, rather than through direct command invocation."}]},"uuid":"8b7c2516-76bf-43ef-9e83-d15cd9956f12","timestamp":"2025-12-04T15:55:46.854Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":249486,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Model Context Protocol (MCP) - Available Commands\n\nBased on the web page content, MCP itself is not a command-line tool with specific commands. Rather, it's **an open-source standard for connecting AI applications to external systems**.\n\n## What MCP Enables\n\nThe protocol allows AI applications to:\n\n- **Access data sources** (local files, databases)\n- **Utilize tools** (search engines, calculators)\n- **Execute workflows** (specialized prompts)\n\nThe page describes MCP as functioning \"like a USB-C port for AI applications,\" providing standardized connectivity.\n\n## Development Resources\n\nThe documentation outlines paths for developers:\n\n1. **Build MCP servers** - to expose data and tools\n2. **Build MCP clients** - applications that connect to MCP servers\n3. **Use SDKs** - official tools for implementation\n4. **MCP Inspector** - for testing and debugging servers\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nMCP is an **architectural standard and protocol**, not a command-line utility with discrete commands. Users interact with it through client applications (like Claude Desktop) that integrate with MCP servers, rather than through direct command invocation.","durationMs":5767,"url":"https://modelcontextprotocol.io/"}}
